note as RelationshipCorrections
  <b>Relationship cardinalities corrected by LLM review</b>
  Actor "1" *-- "*" Permission → Actor "1" -- "*" Permission
    Reason: Composition (many left, one right) is incorrect; an Actor has many Permissions, so undirected association with one-to-many is appropriate. Id 1 already shows the correct association.
  AlternativeRunway "*" ..> AircraftType → AlternativeRunway "*" -- "*" AircraftType
    Reason: Dependency with cardinality is misplaced; many AlternativeRunways can accommodate many AircraftTypes, so many-to-many association is more accurate.
  AlternativeRunway "1" -- "1" Runway → AlternativeRunway "*" -- "1" Runway
    Reason: One-to-one is too restrictive; a closed runway can have many alternative runways, so many alternative runways associated with one runway (a runway has many alternatives).
  Flight "1" -- "0..*" Slot → Flight "1" -- "1" Slot
    Reason: Each flight has exactly one active slot at a time; the existing zero-to-many multiplicity contradicts the one-to-one relationship in id 10. Corrected to one-to-one.
  Flight "1" -- "0..1" CriticalFlight → CriticalFlight --|> Flight
    Reason: A critical flight is a subtype of Flight, not an associated entity. Swapped classes and used inheritance to reflect that CriticalFlight extends Flight.
  Flight "1" -- "0..1" EmergencyStateMarker → Flight "1" *-- "1" EmergencyStateMarker
    Reason: Each flight owns one emergency state marker as part of its lifecycle; one-to-one composition (Flight contains EmergencyStateMarker) is more appropriate than association.
  FlightAssignment "1" -- "1" TimeSlot → FlightAssignment "1" ..> "1" TimeSlot
    Reason: The direct Flight-Slot association (id 10) already models the allocation; FlightAssignment should only depend on TimeSlot, not have a separate association, to avoid redundancy.
  Operation "1" *-- "1" Interface → Operation "1" --> "1" Interface
    Reason: An Operation uses an Interface, but composition implies ownership; directed association is more appropriate for a usage relationship.
  Resource "1" *-- "*" Actor → Resource "*" -- "*" Actor
    Reason: A Resource is not composed of Actors; many Actors can use many Resources, so many-to-many association is correct.
  Resource "1" *-- "1" Actor → Resource "1" -- "1" Actor
    Reason: Composition is incorrect; a simple one-to-one association between Resource and Actor (e.g., a resource currently assigned to one actor) is more plausible.
  Slot "0..1" -- "1" Runway → Slot "1" -- "1" Runway
    Reason: Each slot is assigned to exactly one runway; the zero-or-one multiplicity on Slot side is incorrect—a slot cannot exist without a runway.
end note

note as ArchitectureCorrections
  <b>Architecture mistakes corrected automatically</b>
  [wrong_class_type] FlightDataStore is declared as an interface but is used as a concrete data store for Flight entities.
    Fix applied: change_class_type
  [wrong_class_type] RunwaySlotDB is declared as an interface but is used as a concrete database for runway slot data.
    Fix applied: change_class_type
  [wrong_class_type] TimetableUI is declared as an interface but represents a concrete user interface component.
    Fix applied: change_class_type
  [wrong_inheritance] CriticalFlight inherits from Flight, but the domain describes emergency as a state of a flight, not a separate entity.
    Fix applied: remove_relation
  [missing_relationship] FlightAssignment should have a direct association with Flight, not just a dependency on TimeSlot.
    Fix applied: add_relation
  [missing_relationship] Runway should have a direct association with TimeSlot to support slot allocation per runway.
    Fix applied: add_relation
  [duplicate_concept] Slot and TimeSlot appear to represent the same concept (a time slot for a flight). They should be merged.
    Fix applied: merge_classes
  [other_correction] EmergencyStateMarker is a composition inside Flight, but emergency is a state that should be an attribute or enum, not a separate class.
    Fix applied: remove_relation
end note

